European inflation slipped into food
The accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is first due to the rapid growth in the price of food products.
The price increase in November has been higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, registering - after 2.6 percent in October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - announced the Union Statistics Office based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were only likely 3 percent - Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the North American, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the basic interest, on the pretext that the decline, along with rising prices of raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, would cause a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least about two percent.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "you have to negotiate" on inflation so that later it does not have to intervene in this issue.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, registered in Germany, broke the record of twelve years; while in Spain it rose from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation soared in the euro area as a result of galloping food and energy prices.
The completion prices of wheat increased by 88 percent and the price of soybeans also reached its highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil in the world market rose this year by 52 percent, reaching black gold almost 100 dollars a barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent, by contrast to 2009 it will decline to 1.9.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain in the next 3 or 4 months around 3 percent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to double the interest rates by the ECB during 2008.
Gallup foresees a government crisis
After a long stagnation, by early December the support of the Young Democrats Alliance increased significantly, reaching its peak since 2002, while the Gallup never experienced such a low level – 13 percent – in the case of the socialists.
The difference in the case of the safe voters of the parties - due to the greater firmness of the opposition voters - would mean support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) compared to the support of a fifth for the socialists (20 percent).
According to the poll, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not reach the necessary limit to have any parliamentary scale: their support within the entire population is two percent.
Among the safe voters there are one percent more supporters on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the lowest point before - the proportion of those who judged the economic situation in the country has never been so high, 41 percent, while another 46 percent believe that the situation is quite bad.
Families, after the hopeless expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about changing their own economic situation.
As far as the next year is concerned, the majority of the population has the deteriorating situation and only one tenth expects improvement.
In December, 71 percent of respondents, higher than any previous Gallup poll, estimated that the President of Government rather detracts badly than his functions.
13 percent of respondents trust or trust Ferenc Gyurcsány a lot, while Viktor Orbán has the support of 38 percent of those consulted.
54 percent of the population do not trust the Head of Government at all and 27 percent do not trust the president of the Alliance of Young Democrats.
One of the indicators of the configuration of the political situation is that, what proportion of society thinks that it is possible to control the discontent experienced against the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
While after the October riots of last year 35 percent estimated that it would be desirable to keep the Government and the Head of Government in power, this proportion is currently only 20 percent, while the relative majority (33 percent) believe that the only solution is the holding of new elections.
Interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 percent of respondents to the stake question responded that they would participate surely and another 20 percent said they are likely to participate.
By way of comparison, in "a general election to be held this Sunday" would participate safely only 55 percent of the population and another 15 percent believe their participation is likely. Based on the current intentions of the voters there is no doubt about the outcome of the popular consultation.
74 percent of the population would disapprove of the payment of study fees, 79 percent of the service of medical consultations and 84 percent of hospital care.
If we look at these proportions only among the safe participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would refuse the introduction of study rights, payment for medical consultations and that of hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has quintupled its prices
The average price level rise of 16 percent maintained the hypermarkets of the Budaörs gold trade triangle, with the difference that this year has not increased VAT.
Article by Napi Gazdaság
This year also increased by an average of 16 percent in the commercial gold triangle of Budaörs the usual Christmas basket of the newspaper Napi, but in all hypermarkets there was a growth much higher than the HUF thousand.
As in December of last year, prices had already "skyrocketed" in food supermarkets, so a drastic percentage increase was not experienced compared to the high starting point.
However, it is evidently terrifying for consumers that what the past year could buy at a price well below the nine thousand HUF, today they cannot do it for ten thousand.
The Napi basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded with a minimum of 91 HUF the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF.
And the highest-value basket was 10 573 HUF.
(in 2003 that basket cost 6800 HUF.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the level of the previous year, but there was a sharp increase in turkey breast fillet, walnut and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed data from the Central Bureau of Statistics, although in the Auchan we have also found a kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
Competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was also surprising in this store that the price of Coca-Cola with a redeemable bottle of two liters cost less than 200 HUF, so that this product, even with the price of the bottle, cost only 257 HUF.
However, in Napi Auchan’s basket it was the most expensive, while Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, with respect to Christmas prices last year, Cora increased with 15, while Tesco and Auchan with about 18 percent the prices listed in the Napi basket.
Comparing the values of the most expensive basket of the past year with that of the cheapest basket of this year, the difference has been 12 percent, while the growth between the cheapest of the past year and the most expensive of this year has been 21 percent.
The average growth was 1480 HUF.
The average price growth last year was 1206 HUF, so that during Christmas last year in prices the increase in VAT was felt.
This process was precisely the one that destroyed trade, supermarkets were visibly unable to make a decision on the price margin to be applied for each product and to calculate the effect of the price change on consumption.
(If the trader poorly plans the speed of a product’s circulation, he may lose a significant profit in the margin that fits the sales volume.)
The increase in the price of the Napi basket reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, that the most expensive was higher with 1720 HUF at the value registered in 2006, while in the cheapest the difference was only an 844 HUF.
This year did not produce such extremes, since the highest price now has been 1630 HUF more than the past year and the cheapest also increased with 1284 HUF.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, there was catastrophic growth in prices in less than 20 months, in the hypermarkets grew more than 30 percent the price of basic consumer items.
(However this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Bureau of Statistics: this office, in the case of some basic foods, registered in the 12-month interval a price increase of more than 30 percent.
For example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of egg.)
According to the Napi basket, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, because in the price of this product that was quite expensive already last year compared to the base, it was recorded, in the worst case just a 10 percent increase in prices.
According to all the indices, flour suppliers have a stronger position than egg suppliers, being able to impose the drastic increase in prices even on multinationals.
Hypermarkets do not complain about the gold trading triangle, they constantly talk about positive results.
According to our collected experiences, most consumers in the three stores visited are no longer interested in prices.
Of all the products they buy large quantities, taking preserved food by pallets.
In Wednesday’s morning, large queues were formed in the three stores ahead of the boxes because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that in the interior of the country sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to survey institutes because income is below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in that of household appliances.
In many hospitals you save with disinfectants
This year several thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals in the first place due to the improper application of antibiotics.
The prevailing hygiene circumstances in hospitals, the overcrowding of the beds and the overload of the staff do not favor the control of infections - says the doctor-head of department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
In many hospitals it saves even with disinfectants.
Not long ago, an infection with MRSA has been diagnosed in the trauma department of the Hospital János.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of the antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of contagion occurred in this same hospital at the beginning of the year.
One injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient shortly after had to return to the hospital as a result of the contagion with MRSA and since then a significant surgical intervention has not been possible due to the presence of the bacteria in his body.
As of December 10, 10 of this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection by multi-resistant agents have been registered in the National System Nosocomialis Surveillance - said Karolina Böröcz, medical-head of department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that in hospitals surely this number of infections caused by multi-resistant agents has been recorded, the rest of them have no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to the MRSA, i.e. the methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
One-third of humans carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their nose without causing any disease.
SA infections (e.g., throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once it is exaggerated or improperly applied to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics are transformed into bacteria that are very resistant to antibiotics and spread rapidly in inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, for example wound infections or sepsis first of all to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, patients with weakened organism, elderly or low-weighted people.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the Hospital János there is nothing special in the infection of the MRSA, these infections are daily in hospitals.
Infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotic resistant
"These patients are isolated, the nurses care for them in rubber gloves and mask and there are the right antibiotics for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are pre-screened to verify the presence of MRSA in their body, but not even so infection can be prevented in all cases.
It is not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent hospital infections of the MRSA in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of training and contagion with multi-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate the patients who carry the MRSA in their bodies.
However, in Hungarian hospitals, microbiological sampling is not fashionable.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not fund these medical examinations.
So most cases come to light when visible MRSA infections already occur in the patient - said the doctor-head of department of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes strict entrustments for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological conditions.
It must be emphanized that antibiotic therapy is targeted, that is, microbiological examinations should be done to prevent resistance to drugs, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less frequent for traveling patients or basic care, said Karolina Böröcz.
Saves with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is spread from one patient to another through healthcare personnel.
Therefore, a very important role plays a lot of hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks, however also in this sense considerable faults are experienced in hospitals.
MRSA is spread by drop transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital wards are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated by at least a distance of 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately it can also be experienced - added Karolina Böröcz - that in hospitals of less favorable economic situation is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and that is why there is a greater probability for infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate prevention measures are met, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the contagion of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
The treatment of contagion with MRSA is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so in all countries it is fought against it.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce cases of MRSA.
The programme appears to be successful, according to the data supplied, MRSA infections show a declining trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including the MRSA) and that of hospital infections that are due to these pathogens.
