400 million euros more for infrastructure
Hungarian finance minister János Veres and European Investment Bank (EIB) Vice-President Marta Gajecka signed three credit-limit agreements in Budapest on Friday for a total value of 400 million euros to finance education, transport and environmental infrastructures, as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of 300 million euro to finance in the Hungarian budget the transport and environmental protection projects, which will be carried out of the subsidy of the cohesion funds, of which the parties had previously signed a credit agreement worth 100 million, the contract they have just signed concerns the use of the remaining 200 million euros.
The credit agreement of 150 million euros is also intended to finance the budget of educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of 300 million euros for this objective of Hungary, on the use of the remaining 150 million euros the decision will be made later, when extending the credit contract.
The parties signed a contract for 50 million euros for innovations, which the budget will employ mainly for the innovations and research project of the University of Debrecen.
During the talks they also covered the issue of the construction of the 4th Metro line.
Agreement was reached that by the time Hungary finalized the details of the Metro financing with the EU, they will return to the issue that whether or not it is necessary to modify the original contract and how to do it.
According to János Veres, this can take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990 the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth 8.4 billion euros.
The interest on the claims is in accordance with the EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grace period of 8 years, without charging commission for keeping the credit available to the debtor.
