Fodor and the six for hundreds Hungarians
According to the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, the meetings at the level of experts will be completed on Tuesday and on Wednesday after the official inauguration, negotiations will continue at the level of ministers on the post-2012 international climate regime.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world deliberate on the Bali Road Map available on post-emissions reduction efforts, as set out in the Kyoto Protocol, up to 2012.
There are currently lively discussions about the particular between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that for the moment it does not want to negotiate on precise figures, although it tends to reach the agreement that compared to the situation of 1990, until 2020 the emission of gases responsible for the greenhouse effect decreases by 25 to 40 percent.
Another big theme of the conference is that whether or not industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing to offer material and technological assistance to countries in need.
Agreement was also reached on aid to provide developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a 16-member board of directors, probably within the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF) - writes the "Piac is Profit".
The six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to retain its leading role in global climate protection and promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 20 percent, regardless of whether or not the “post-2012 agreement” will be signed and is willing to commit to reducing even 30 percent if the world’s other large developed regions and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in line with their responsibility and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the signatory countries of the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed to decrease by 5.2 percent, among this the then 15 EU member states committed to meet an 8 percent decrease.
Hungary’s commitment is to reduce the emission of greenhouse gases by 6 percent compared to the period between 1985 and 87, which our country will comply with – the press release of the Ministry of the Environment is scheduled.
Much is at stake in Bali, since within two years the international long-term climate policy agreement will have to be signed, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed to after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments made in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international emission reduction system, whose need was warned in its most recent report by the IPCC, the UN international scientific association that deals with climate change, which won the Nobel Peace Prize.
With this, the reduction of emissions would suffer a delay and could not prevent an increase of more than 2o C of the average temperature of the Earth, a fact that according to the scientists would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
British Army Recruits on YouTube
British army units in a video distributor publish recordings of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) was the one that took advantage of YouTube services: special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos about their actions against the Taliban - the BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in the general body of operations of Kandahar, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
Already 139 recordings from the air force soldiers that have been loaded in this way to the Internet and their "channel" has already been seen by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in the spring of 2007 under the name of "defence headquarters" and publishes videos of both actions perpetrated in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Ministry of the Commonwealth of British Nations (Commonwealth Office) and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had loaded the videos with recruitment objectives, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defence they also serve to present to the public the true objective of the presence of the British army abroad.
This type of propaganda costs practically nothing compared to conventional television recruitment spots - declared to the BBC the defense expert Gordon Mackenzie - instead, inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the raison d'être of the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans prepared a video game
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the highly edited and censored recordings, the distributor also includes amateur videos, for example about the death of the soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers speak at most of losses, without presenting the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan have already uploaded to the Internet numerous videos recorded in real operations, but the British army is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different way for recruitment with the free downloadable shooter video games called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can put themselves directly in place of the soldiers.
