A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidential nature, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which describe the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitlerite regime, are in free access.
The 47 million documents of archives, stored on 27 km of shelves to Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not so far consultable only in a "humanitarian" purpose, that is to say individually and nominatively, at the request of a former victim or his right-holders.
The eleven states responsible for their management - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to search engines and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening is effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow search "in particular on the displacement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the health status of the forced workers", explains Reto Meistern, the director of these files administered by the International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, such as Germany, opposed the opening to the public of these nominative documents, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the supposed homosexuality or mental handicap of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been gathered after war in a practical purpose: to find the countrymen deported or subjected to compulsory work and, eventually, to provide them with proof of their internment, in order to open the way to their compensation.
Still today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent wage earners deal with tens of thousands of individual petitions.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to be expected from these documents," Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Centre for the Search for Anti-Semitism at the Technische Universität in Berlin, said in 2006.
