Car insurance, which covers the driver before possible accidents, is a significant expense that will depend on various factors, such as age, sex, age of the license, marital status, type of vehicle to be insured or the use of this, among others.
Having the car is just the beginning.
Choosing the right car insurance is even harder than choosing the vehicle model.
First of all, we have to be clear about what we are talking about.
Car insurance is an agreement between an insurance company and the insured.
This commitment materializes in an insurance contract, which establishes that the company receives the value of the agreed premium in exchange for being responsible for the obligation to pay the compensation in the event of a claim.
The premium is the price of insurance, which is established taking into account various factors, such as age, sex, age of the license, marital status, type of vehicle to be insured or the use of this, among others.
Insurance companies set their prices according to statistics, so that the more likely they are to suffer an accident, the higher the share to be paid.
That’s why both those over 25 and women have to pay lower premiums, as statistics reflect that they have a lower rate of accident rate due to their caution.
Also, using the counts, companies have concluded that married people tend to have fewer accidents than single drivers.
The use that is given to the vehicle will influence the frequency, and with it on the probability of having some type of mishap.
Increasing the frequency increases the odds.
There are many variables that insurers take into account when setting the price of the premium.
That is why the driver has to study the situation well to choose that car insurance that best fits his profile.
We will present here the most significant variables when choosing one or another type of insurance, so that this, in addition to adapting to the characteristics of the insured, offers you a reasonable price.
Young people under 25 find themselves with various inconvenience when it comes to contracting insurance at an affordable price, such as the reduced driving experience and the age of the card.
Although the ideal to be well insured is a full-risk insurance, there are other cheaper options.
The most cautious drivers can opt for a full risk with franchise, so that they get the coverage of a full-risk insurance but at a more feasible price.
This type of agreement would mean that the client pays a part of the amount of the claim.
"The part of the amount of the accident that the customer contributes will be pre-established according to the value of the premium, which will be higher the lower the amount," says Luis Noguera, head of First Europe, online insurance mediator.
Another option is extended third-party insurance, so that the customer ensures protection against damage to third parties, although not in the face of those caused in their own car.
In addition, it would be covered by theft, fire and loss of the vehicle.
A tip.
If you are under 25 try to be careful and avoid claims as much as possible, since this will have an impact on the bonus, being able to reduce the cost of insurance in the future.
A bonus is a reduction on the base rate the company owns.
On the contrary, a penalty is a surcharge on that base rate.
"The bonuses and penalties will depend on the company and the benefit of the company.
If the company has had a good year it can afford to increase the bonuses, "clarifies Noguera.
After the 25-year-old range, drivers have it easier to take out insurance, since the accident rate is reduced thanks to the accumulated experience.
For this reason, it is best to hire a full risk with franchise.
"Normally young people can not make use of the experience previously acquired when it comes to being used in an accident, and even at the time of driving," says the director in Spain of the European company, to which he adds that most of the accidents occur in the second year of driving, once the 'fear of the rookie' has passed.
However, if the client is married but still has no children it is preferable to negotiate insurance at all risk, as long as their economic situation allows it, of course.
For their part, marriages with children are considered by insurers as the public with the lowest rate of accident rate, so the surcharges will be lower.
In this case the best insurance would be one at full risk with franchise (can be this of 300 euros), or, when a high level of bonus is available, one to third party extended from the third year of life of the vehicle.
"They carry out a more relaxed driving and have greater purchasing power to allow themselves the luxury of assuming a greater amount of franchise," says Luis Noguera.
For retirees it is recommended a full insurance with franchise (this being 150 euros), or one to third parties extended when you have a high level of bonus.
It must be said that car insurance is something important, not only because it covers the driver before possible accidents, but also because it represents a significant expense, which is why it is essential to adequately study the insurance that best suits us according to our personal situation.
