Venus: twin brother of Earth.
Despite its atmosphere it is not suitable for life, Venus is the most Earth-like planet, something that until now had not been considered. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and swirls at the poles, the same that also appear in winter on Earth.
For three decades, researchers had suspected that lightning might exist on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus the rays fall from a height of 54 kilometers of one cloud and behind another, Cris Russell of the University of California, Los Angeles, told the scientific journal "Nature".
According to the famous model of the origin of Urey-Miller’s life, the rays caused life on Earth: the storms may have provoked reactions in the ocean that, for their part, would have given rise to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
On Venus it is not like this: if there was life there one day, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
Today, on the surface of Venus there can be no life: the atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times greater than on Earth and on the surface temperatures of 500°C reign, oscillating in such a way that sub-zero temperatures can be reached.
"Possibly Venus is a "diabolical" twin of Earth, but it's still a twin," Russell said.
The main goal of the Venus Express mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth for its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since the 1990s there have been no special missions, just for research on this planet, the launch of Venus-Express in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus research.
The latest research results to be presented in many Nature articles, according to the researchers, underscore not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"This also shows that neighboring planets have more common characteristics with Earth than we had assumed," ESA reports.
Despite the well-known stormy winds at the North Pole, the researchers discovered in the southern polar region also a vortex formed by the fastest spinning clouds.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the high atmospheric terrestrial layers of the poles, according to a team of researchers from Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet in the Solar System has the almost equal mass to Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers is almost as large.
This planet also called the alba star or evening star orbits the Sun almost 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day on Venus equals 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bar does not closely resemble Earth, scientists start from the base that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
On the two planets there was water that on Earth stayed in the oceans, but on Venus it dissociated itself in the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, on Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
